<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="123" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[136,1451,2022,2084]" lastBlockId="18.[136,1452,158,617]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="123" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,397,2022,2048]" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. E. Fries" authorityYear="1908" box="[426,575,2022,2048]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="regnellii">
<emphasis box="[426,575,2022,2048]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Sida regnellii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to section 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fryxell" authorityYear="1985" baseAuthorityName="de Candolle" box="[784,912,2022,2048]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Cordifoliae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[784,912,2022,2048]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Cordifoliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the indument densely stellate-tomentose; leaf blades lanceolate to ovate, dentate-crenate throughout, basally more or less cordate, features pointed out by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fryxell, P. A." lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="123" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" pagination="62 - 91" refId="ref18743" refString="Fryxell, P. A. (1985) The North and Central American species of Sida. Sida, Contributions to Botany 11: 62 - 91." type="journal article" year="1985">Fryxell (1985)</bibRefCitation>
for this section (
<tableCitation box="[395,478,158,184]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,340,364]" captionTargetBox="[144,1440,425,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sections of Sida with species occurring in Rio Grande do Sul state, and their diagnostic features, according to Fryxell (1985) and Krapovickas (2003)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39" pageId="18" pageNumber="123" tableUuid="539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39">Table 1</tableCitation>
). It can be distinguished from similar species by its muticous or submuticous mericarps (with aristae up to 
<quantity box="[346,432,194,221]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="123" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
long) and by the pink corolla (
<figureCitation box="[777,938,194,220]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[136,229,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,190,1896]" captionTargetId="figure-17@19.[190,1398,190,1896]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. A–E. Sida regnellii. A. Flower. B. Adaxial surface of leaf. C. Branch with flower, leaves and mature schizocarp. D. Habit. E. Branch with leaves and mature schizocarps. F–J. Sida rhombifolia. F, G. Flowers. H. Abaxial surface of leaf. I. Adaxial surface of leaf. J. Branch with mature mericarps. L–P. Sida riedelii. L. Flower. M. Branch with leaves, flower bud and mature mericarp. N.Adaxial surface of leaf. O. Abaxial surface of leaf. P. Branch with tubercle at petiole base. Photographs by Martin Grings and Sérgio A.L. Bordignon (D)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415507" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415507/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Figures 9A–E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[950,1001,194,220]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-54@26.[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 14. Mericarps. A. Sida anomala. B. Sida confusa. C. Sida farroupilhensis. D. Sida glaziovii. E. Sida cerradoensis. F. Sida cordifolia. G. Sida dubia. H. Sida linifolia. I. Sida lonchitis. J. Sida nemorensis. K. Sida paradoxa. L. Sida planicaulis. M. Sida potentilloides.N. Sida reitzii. O. Sida regnellii. P. Sida rhombifolia.Q. Sida riedelii. R. Sida rubifolia.S. Sida spinosa.T. Sida tuberculata. U. Sida urens. V. Sida viarum. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415519/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">14O</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
